ownedComment.body: Suggest renaming to "communication profile." The term "profile" is used in multiple contexts within ITS and thus adding "communication" is valuable. It is unclear what "ITS-S" adds to the context. It is also unclear that this is different than the protocol stack since all of the defined "parameters" appear to be comments and non-normative.

Here there is at least an argument for the "ITS" prefix since the identifiers are assigned by our own registry. Likewise, the "ID" postfix is justified since this is the identifier. One can then argue the merits of using a shorter name with an abbreviation or using a longer name to be more consistent with defined terms.

Suggest renaming to "protocol" as we often use non-ITS protocols and ITS-developed protocols can be used outside of ITS (at least in theory). Likewise "communication" does not add any real information as we generally do not use the term "protocol" in any other context (and it is not a part of our abbreviated forms). If we shorten the term, we don't need an abbreviated form and our documents become easier to understand.

Suggest renaming to "protocol stack parameter" or perhaps better yet, "protocol stack requirements" as the term "Parameter" here is apparently used differently than it is in the case of an ITS-S communication profile. i.e., in the ITS-S communication profile examples, the parameters seem to point to regulations and other information. This concept (CSP_SpecificCommProts) does not provide a mechansim to convey such information. While it is called a communication service parameter, it only passes an identifier for an ITS-SCPS per the ASN.1 and there is no mechanism to pass additional information as a part of the structure.
Do we need something like cooperative route to describe carpooling/vanpooling or is this adequately covered by fixed/dymanic route? (coupled with a cooperative financial model)
Should there be a separate term for self-propelled vehicles that are being towed?

properties.documentation:
This concept model is intended to formally document the vocabulary used and developed by the entire intelligent transport systems (ITS) community. The terms and definitions are developed in an open environment according to the principles defined in Annex A of ISO 14812 with specific versions formally adopted through updates to ISO 14812.
It is recognized that the contents of this model are not exhaustive, and that terminology evolves over time. ISO/TC 204 and other ITS experts are encouraged to adopt the definitions included within this model within their discussions and especially in formal documentation; however, it is recognized that each document may need to define additional terms to meet its own needs.
Annex B of ISO 14812 provides the best practices for defining and referencing terms in industry documentation.
The process to suggest changes to the model can be found at the UML Best Practices repository of this GitHub site.
In most cases, the definitions provided within this document are suitable for general application throughout ITS. In those circumstances where the definition only applies within a restricted context, the context is indicated at the beginning of the definition.
EDITORS NOTE: To facilitate the review of this model by others, the attached Microsoft Excel file maps each of the terms defined in this document to similar terms defined in existing ISO/TC 204 documents, along with the definitions for those terms and the WGs responsible for developing and maintaining those documents.

tag.value: #NOTES#C-ITS does not preclude two parties from having a separate bi-lateral agreement, but any services requiring a bi-lateral agreement would not technically be considered "C-ITS". For example, two emergency vehicles may have a bi-lateral agreement to share incident information containing sensitive data; such a service would not be considered C-ITS, since it is under a bi-lateral agreement. However, the same two vehicles may share vehicle location and motion information for collision avoidance purposes; this would be considered C-ITS since the agreement to share that information is under the broader use case that uses a third-party agreement.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: #NOTES#Most current-day computer systems rely upon an agreement between the owners or users of the two systems involved in an exchange. For example, there is typically bi-lateral agreement between a provider and a user. C-ITS instead relies upon a system of third-party agreements. In other words, a third party defines the rules for operating within a domain and creates a trust network. Providers and users establish agreements with the third party agreeing to abide by the rules. Providers and users then directly interact based on the rules of the trust network without requiring any direct relationship between the two.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: #NOTES#There is not complete agreement on the precise limits of ITS. Currently, the term is almost exclusively applied to ground-based travel of goods and people over significant distances. The term is viewed as including ferry systems, which often form an integral part of a local surface transport system; it is less clear if it includes long-distance sea-fairing ships. ITS is also generally applied to transport systems that cover a considerable distance (e.g., control systems for factory conveyance technologies are not often referred to as "ITS"). Some have suggested that air travel, which is arguably a transport system designed to move physical entities between points on the surface of the earth, should be included in the scope of the term, but this perspective is not universally accepted. It is expected that the exact limits of the term will be further refined as the technology matures.

Suggest renaming to "protocol stack parameter" or perhaps better yet, "protocol stack requirements" as the term "Parameter" here is apparently used differently than it is in the case of an ITS-S communication profile. i.e., in the ITS-S communication profile examples, the parameters seem to point to regulations and other information. This concept (CSP_SpecificCommProts) does not provide a mechansim to convey such information. While it is called a communication service parameter, it only passes an identifier for an ITS-SCPS per the ASN.1 and there is no mechanism to pass additional information as a part of the structure.
Suggest renaming to "protocol parameter"
Suggest renaming to protocol stack

Suggest renaming to "protocol" as we often use non-ITS protocols and ITS-developed protocols can be used outside of ITS (at least in theory). Likewise "communication" does not add any real information as we generally do not use the term "protocol" in any other context (and it is not a part of our abbreviated forms). If we shorten the term, we don't need an abbreviated form and our documents become easier to understand.

Here there is at least an argument for the "ITS" prefix since the identifiers are assigned by our own registry. Likewise, the "ID" postfix is justified since this is the identifier. One can then argue the merits of using a shorter name with an abbreviation or using a longer name to be more consistent with defined terms.

Suggest renaming to "communication profile." The term "profile" is used in multiple contexts within ITS and thus adding "communication" is valuable. It is unclear what "ITS-S" adds to the context. It is also unclear that this is different than the protocol stack since all of the defined "parameters" appear to be comments and non-normative.

tag.value: Local legislation might allow cycleways to be used by a variety of low-speed vehicles (e.g., low-speed scooters, skateboards, etc.) and might share usage of other low-speed modes such as pedestrians, horseback riders, etc.

properties.documentation: infrastructure primarily designed for the movement of pedestrians

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: A paved footway is called a "pavement" in the British English and a "sidewalk" in American English.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Regulations typically allow footways to be used by other ultra-low speed users, such as the users of wheelchairs and strollers.

properties.documentation: infrastructure designed for the movement of both pedestrians and cyclists within the same space

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: A shared-use way is designed for pedestrians and cyclists to share the use of the same area; a facility that separates pedestrians and cyclists to different areas (even if part of the same facility) should be identified as separate footways and cycleways.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Regulations typically allow shared-use ways to be used by other ultra-low and low speed users, such as the users of wheelchairs, strollers, horseback riders, etc.

properties.documentation: operating mode of a hard shoulder that allows operation of emergency, construction, maintenance, or other special use vehicles or for emergency stopping and is prohibited for other vehicle usage
operating mode of a hard shoulder that allows operation of general-purpose vehicles as an extra lane
link that represents a lane of a road link

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: A lane segment might start or end at locations other than the start or end of the corresponding road segment (e.g., a lane may start mid-block).

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: A lane segment only includes the sequential lane links, it does not include lane links from adjacent lanes.

properties.documentation: link that represents a contiguous length of a lane link characterized by the same physical characteristics
<road network> component of a road model that represents a connection between two nodes

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: A link might be curvilinear and might have various attributes such as width.

properties.documentation: <road network> component of a road model representing a point location of the road network graph

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The point location typically represents a point along the road which might be used to designate the location of a junction, public transport stop, jurisdictional boundary, termination point, etc.

properties.documentation: curvilinear length of driving space that shares the same identification

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The identification is generally a name or number.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: A length of the road network may be referenced by multiple designators (e.g., Main Street and Route 7). In this case, there would be two "roads" that share the same set of "carriageways".

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: A road may change directions at a junction.

properties.documentation: link representing a contiguous length of a road between two nodes of operational or managerial significance

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: #NOTES#The operational characteristics of the nodes would relate to the type of road model. For example, a traffic system might base its road links on nodes that represent junctions and road terminators.

properties.documentation: representation of a road network

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: #NOTES#Road models for different systems will often define different models. For example, a public transport system might define road links based on the location of bus stops while a traffic system might define road links based on the location of junctions.

properties.documentation: interconnected collection of roads
aggregation of one or more road links that represents a contiguous length of a road that shares the same management and operational strategies

tag.name: Vocab::example
tag.value: A traffic signal timing plan is applied to one road section.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Different road models might divide the same road into different road sections.

properties.documentation: link that represents a contiguous length of a road link characterized by the same physical characteristics

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: #NOTES#The definition of road segments is highly dependent on what characteristics are modelled by the implementation. Characteristics that might result in a new road segment include addition or subtraction of a lane, a change in driving space width, the change of road type (e.g., start/end of a bridge), etc.

properties.documentation: traffic lane designed for exiting a junction
all egress lanes on a road link
manoeuvre that is vertically separated from one or more manoeuvres that cross its two-dimensional path
traffic lane designed for entering a junction
all ingress lanes on a road link
junction with at least one grade separated manoeuvre

tag.name: Vocab::example
tag.value: #NOTES#A common diamond interchange is a single junction that has at least one grade separated manoeuvre and six intersections: two crossing intersections (where slip roads meet the cross road), two diverge points (where slip roads start, and two merge points (where slip roads end).

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The grade separation allows travellers on the link to pass unimpeded through the junction when congestion is not present.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The concept of an interchange includes all available manoeuvres at the junction, which can include multiple intersections.

properties.documentation: point or space, operated as a single entity, at which two or more traffic flows meet as a part of a junction

tag.name: Vocab::example
tag.value: #NOTES#An at-grade junction of two dual carriageway road segments would be considered a single intersection if traffic operations at the junction are determined by a single set of control logic (e.g., a traffic signal); however, such a junction could be operated as four distinct intersections (i.e., four distinct crossings of one-way carriageways), especially if the road segments have large central reservations.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: #NOTES#While the term "junction" relates to roads, which can be bi-directional, the term "intersection" relates to traffic flows, which are always uni-directional. A simple junction is likely to have a single intersection. A complex junction generally has multiple intersections.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The term "intersection" includes roundabouts that operate as a single entity; it does not include a traffic circle with distinct areas of control (e.g., multiple traffic signals).

properties.documentation: space where two or more roads meet in a manner that allows travellers to change roads
junction without any grade separated manoeuvres
<junction> movement from an ingress lane to an egress lane

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The term "maneuver" is the American English spelling.

properties.documentation: <ITS> spatial location enclosed within two-dimensional boundary/boundaries across a defined surface

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The boundary may consist of a single (e.g., a circle) or multiple (e.g., the boundaries of city limits) curvilinear lines and might consist of multiple enclosed areas.

properties.documentation: well defined geographic place described by one coordinate tuple

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The "geolocation" term is a short version of the term used within some ITS communities.

properties.documentation: <ITS> spatial location that extends between two point locations along a defined path
particular place or position

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The term "location" by itself is a broad term that can be used to reference spatial, computer memory, imaginary, and other locations.

properties.documentation: spatial location with no length in any of the spatial dimensions
<ITS> location within three-dimensional space

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The "location" could be a point (consuming no space) or could consume space in one, two, or three dimensions. In any case, the location is identified within a larger space.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Within ITS, locations are typically locations on or near the surface of the earth.

properties.documentation: spatial reference generated on-the-fly based on geographic properties in a digital map database
register of spatial references of one or more location sub-types containing some information regarding position

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The positional information need not be coordinates but could be descriptive.

tag.name: Vocab::source
tag.value: ISO 19112:2019, 3.1.1, modified to fit our concept model

properties.documentation: spatial reference in the form of a label or code

tag.name: Vocab::example
tag.value: "Spain" is an example of a label (country name); "SW1P 3AD" is an example of a code (postcode).

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The term "location code" has been used previously in ISO/TC 204 standards, but "geographic identifier" is preferred to be more consistent with ISO/TC 211 work.

tag.name: Vocab::source
tag.value: ISO 19112:2019, 3.1.2, note and deprecated term added

properties.documentation: pre-coded spatial reference defined within the road network database
<ITS> process used to develop a spatial reference
spatial reference using a unique identifier that is agreed upon in both sender and receiver system to select a location from a set of pre-coded locations
<ITS> description of a spatial location in the real world according to a defined reference system

tag.value: Description: 110 m northwest from intersection of Blackheath Avenue and Great Cross Avenue.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The rules need not be formal coordinates but could be descriptive.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The term "location reference" has been used within ITS, but the term "spatial reference" is preferred to better align with activities of ISO/TC 211.

properties.documentation: performance of one or more tasks or provision of one or more facilities to enable one or more tasks to fulfil a need for a user
entity that delivers one or more services
entity that has a need to be fulfilled

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The term "consumer" can be used when fulfilling the need results in the consumption of a resource.

properties.documentation: factor or condition necessary to achieve desired results within a specified context of use
<transport> material entity that has been, is being, or will be transported
<transport> service that delivers item(s) from one location to another on behalf of a transport consumer to satisfy a need

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The item(s) delivered might be people and/or goods.

properties.documentation: <transport> entity that delivers one or more transport services
<transport> consumer that has a transport need to be fulfilled
<transport> need to transport one or more transport items to a different location
<ITS> performance of one or more tasks to fulfil an ITS user need for an ITS user
<ITS> entity that delivers one or more ITS services
<ITS> entity that has an ITS user need to be fulfilled

<ITS> need of an entity external to the intelligent transport system for a surface transport system benefit that can be met with the use of information, communication, sensor, and/or control technologies

tag.name: Vocab::example
tag.value: Increasing safety, sustainability, efficiency, and/or comfort

properties.documentation: <ITS-S> performance of one or more tasks to fulfil an ITS-S user need for an ITS-S user
<ITS-S> ITS-S that delivers one or more ITS-S services
<ITS-S> entity that has an ITS-S user need to be fulfilled
<ITS-S> need for processing within a bounded, secure, managed domain
<ITS-S> need for communication functionality that connects an ITS-S to other nodes
<ITS-S> entity that delivers one or more ITS-S communication services
<ITS-S> performance of one or more tasks to fulfil an ITS-S communication need for an ITS-S communication user
<ITS-S> entity that has an ITS-S communication need to be fulfilled
transport service delivered by a transport provider that uses the same equipment and/or staff to provide transport services to multiple unrelated transport consumers

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: A shared mobility service can be characterized by its contractual, financial, network, and operational models.

properties.documentation: shared mobility service where the transport provider has the primary responsibility for the selection and operation of the transport mode

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: A shared transport system might not be dependent upon a vehicle and/or could be multi-modal. For example, a letter courier service could rely on walking and public transport.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Responsibilities of the transport service might be further delegated to others. For example, a courier service relying on public transport would delegate the operation of the transport mode to the public transport operator.

properties.documentation: shared mobility service where the transport consumer has the primary responsibility for the operation of the vehicle

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: As there should only be one operator of a vehicle at any time, a shared vehicle service should use a sequential operational model.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: This term can be specialized by replacing "vehicle" with any defined vehicle type (e.g., "automated vehicle sharing").

properties.documentation: using a shared transport service
using a shared vehicle service

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: This term can be specialized by replacing "vehicle" with any defined vehicle type; however, in some cases the preferred form is to consolidate terms (e.g., "carsharing" rather than "passenger car sharing").

properties.documentation: <shared mobility> contractual model where the transport provider is a commercial entity or governmental agency and the transport consumer is a commercial entity

tag.name: Vocab::example
tag.value: A business purchasing monthly public transport passes for its employees

tag.name: Vocab::example
tag.value: A commercial entity using a commercial courier service for package delivery

properties.documentation: <shared mobility> contractual model where the transport provider is a commercial entity or governmental agency and the transport consumer is an individual
<shared mobility> contractual model where the transport provider is a commercial entity or governmental agency and the transport consumer is a governmental entity

tag.name: Vocab::example
tag.value: A governmental entity using a commercial courier service for package delivery

properties.documentation: <shared mobility> legal framework used by a shared mobility service

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Contracts might be via a third party, implied or verbal, especially in the case of peer-to-peer.

properties.documentation: <shared mobility> contractual model where both the transport provider and the transport consumer are individuals

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The two individuals may connect and/or contract through a third-party service.

properties.documentation: <shared mobility> financial model where transport services are provided with a profit motive
<shared mobility> financial model where transport consumers partner to defray the costs of transport services

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Cooperative models are exclusive commercial and public models.

properties.documentation: <shared mobility> economic framework used by a shared mobility service
<shared mobility> cooperative financial model where transport consumers partner to support the purchase, maintenance, and overhead costs associated with a vehicle

tag.name: Vocab::preferredTerm
tag.value: shared mobility fractional ownership financial model

properties.documentation: <shared mobility> characteristic of a financial model that requires transport consumers to enter into an agreement prior to receiving transport services

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The membership may be granted as a part of a broader agreement. For example, a university bus system might restrict access to students and faculty.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The agreement might be minimal, such as collecting user information for business purposes.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The agreement might be associated with fees.

properties.documentation: <shared mobility> cooperative financial model where transport consumers partner on a per-trip basis

tag.name: Vocab::preferredTerm
tag.value: shared mobility mutual benefit financial model

properties.documentation: <shared mobility> characteristic of a financial model that does not require membership within an organization to receive transport services

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: This includes models where membership is optional and might provide extra benefits.

properties.documentation: <shared mobility> financial model where transport services are provided to members of the owning organization without usage fees
<shared mobility> financial model where transport services are provided by an administrative authority in an attempt to better serve societal interests

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Typically, the administrative authority is a local government agency; but it could be another administrative authority, such as the national government or a commercial entity managing transport needs on their campus.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The transport service is typically offered to the transport consumer for less than the full capital and operating cost of providing the service, but this is not a requirement.

properties.documentation: <shared transport> operational model where transport services might be provided to multiple transport consumers at any one time
<shared transport> concurrent operation where transported items can only be received or delivered at stopping points within a pre-defined service corridor

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The service corridor often includes a communal point of interest (e.g., an airport, transit hub, etc) as a fixed stopping point.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The service corridor is defined by the provider, who may impose further restrictions on where stops are allowed.

properties.documentation: <shared transport> concurrent operation where transported items can only be received or delivered at stopping points contained in a pre-defined sequence
<shared transport> logistical framework used by a shared mobility service

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The logistical framework might set restrictions on how a passenger and/or good is received, transported, and/or delivered.

properties.documentation: <shared transport> concurrent operation where the transport provider may choose to divert from its path to service a new request from another transport consumer while servicing an earlier transport consumer
<shared transport> operational model where transport services are provided to a single transport consumer at any one time

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: A single transport consumer might request the transport of multiple passengers.

properties.documentation: Do we need something like cooperative route to describe carpooling/vanpooling or is this adequately covered by fixed/dymanic route? (coupled with a cooperative financial model)
<shared mobility> network model where sharing may be initiated and terminated at any location meeting basic criteria

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The basic criteria typically include geographic limits and requirements related to legal and safe locations.

properties.documentation: <shared vehicle> infrastructure framework used by a shared mobility service
<shared vehicle> operational mode where vehicle sharing is initiated and terminated at two different facilities managed by the transport provider

tag.name: Vocab::preferredTerm
tag.value: shared vehicle station-based, one-way network model

properties.documentation: <shared vehicle> operational mode where vehicle sharing is initiated and terminated at the same facility managed by the transport provider

tag.name: Vocab::preferredTerm
tag.value: shared vehicle station-based, roundtrip network model

properties.documentation: commercial, peer-to-peer shared transport service that transports goods

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The goods are typically small packages, letters, food, etc.

properties.documentation: shared transport service that transports passengers and is based on a public financial model

tag.name: Vocab::example
tag.value: city buses, trolleybuses, trams (or light rail), passenger trains, rapid transit (metro/subways/undergrounds, etc.), and ferries

properties.documentation: cooperative shared transport service that transports passengers concurrently
commercial, peer-to-peer shared transport service that transports passengers
ridesourced service that serves passengers concurrently
shared transport service that transports passengers between two specified locations

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Each location might be defined as point, linear, or area locations; however, the areas of the two locations should not overlap.

properties.documentation: commercial shared transport service that transports passengers sequentially
commercial shared transport service that transports passengers concurrently
shared vehicle service that shares bicycles

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The term "bicycle sharing service" is admitted, but "bikesharing service" is preferred as it has fewer syllables.

properties.documentation: shared vehicle service that shares passenger cars

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The term "passenger car sharing service" is admitted but means the same thing.

properties.documentation: mobility app that assists a transport consumer in acquiring shared mobility services from a specific business
ITS-S application implementation designed to assist an individual transport consumer in understanding transport-related information, making decisions, and/or acting upon decisions
mobility app that tracks information about a traveller to provide health-related information

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The information collected may include details such as speed, elapsed travel time, heart rate, etc.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The provided health information might include caloric consumption, peak heart rate, distance travelled, etc.

properties.documentation: mobility app that assists a transport consumer to determine the best route to the destination
mobility app that assists a transport consumer in acquiring shared mobility services from an individual that participates in the mobility app's network
mobility app that assists a transport consumer in using a public transport system

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: A public transport app might include features such as viewing maps, searching routes and schedules, real-time arrival information, ticketing, electronic boarding pass, etc.

properties.documentation: mobility app that provides information about current travel conditions to a transport consumer
P2P mobility sharing app for acquiring a ridesourced service
mobility app that assists a transport consumer in electronically requesting a taxi
mobility app that assists a transport consumer in planning trips that may span multiple vehicle modes or transport providers

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The assistance might include reservations, ticketing, and similar services.

properties.documentation: person who is travelling on foot
mobile entity within the road reservation

tag.name: Vocab::example
tag.value: pedestrians, road work personnel, vehicle occupants, occupied and unoccupied vehicles, horses, etc.

properties.documentation: person, in the role of a transport item, who is headed to a destination
road user other than an occupant of a road vehicle
driver that performs the dynamic driving task using the vehicle's built-in input devices to control the longitudinal and lateral movement of the vehicle
person that is currently responsible for the dynamic driving task for the vehicle

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The driver is typically onboard the vehicle but could be remote from the vehicle or automated logic.

properties.documentation: person who has a reservation to travel or is travelling in a vehicle except for any crew, staff, or drivers
driver that performs the dynamic driving task without using the vehicle's built-in input devices to control the longitudinal and lateral movement of the vehicle

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: A remote driver may use a variety of physical input devices, but not any that are built into the vehicle.

properties.documentation: person in or on a vehicle

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: A vehicle occupant in a stationary vehicle is not necessarily a traveller.

properties.documentation: input device designed to be electronically connected to a vehicle even when the vehicle is not in close proximity
input device designed to be carried into, or in near proximity of, a vehicle and connected as desired

tag.name: Vocab::example
tag.value: A smartphone connected to a vehicle (via USB or Bluetooth) to control the vehicle's audio system

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Nomadic devices are often more closely associated with a person than they are with the vehicle.

properties.documentation: input device designed to be physically connected to a vehicle and to remain connected even when the vehicle is not in use

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Built-in input devices include devices that might be temporarily disconnected for security reasons (e.g., some radios are equipped with detachable front panels).

properties.documentation: material entity that converts energy into mechanical motion
circular material entity that rotates about an axle to facilitate movement of the vehicle
<vehicle> material entity that can affect the vehicle's operation

tag.name: Vocab::example
tag.value: steering wheel, lever, pedal, knob, button, touch screen

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Input devices include those used to control the motion of the vehicle (e.g., a brake pedal), the state of vehicular equipment (e.g., headlight control), the configuration of the vehicle (e.g., temperature control), etc.

properties.documentation: material entity used to transport people or physical goods
<vehicle> maximum speed at which a vehicle is intended to operate for a sustained period of time

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The term "top speed" is defined in SAE J3194:2019 in relation to powered micromobility vehicles and is considered to be semantically equivalent to design speed.

properties.documentation: <vehicle> rate at which a vehicle traverses a curvilinear distance per unit time
driving automation system that is able to perform the entire DDT on a sustained basis

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The abbreviated form ("ADS") is the most preferred form and the alternate form ("Automated Driving System") uses initial capitals to avoid confusion with the more general "driving automation system".

properties.documentation: ADS-equipped vehicle designed for only driverless operation for complete trips
vehicle integrated with an ADS

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: #NOTES#The terms "automated vehicle" and "AV" are often used in a colloquial form, however, these terms might be used to mean either an "ADS-equipped vehicle" or a "vehicle with an engaged ADS". The term "ADS-equipped vehicle" is preferred since it is more precise and descriptive in its meaning.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: This term only describes the capabilities of the vehicle, not its operational state. In other words, the term applies as long as the ADS is connected to the vehicle, whether the DDT is actively engaged or not.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: #NOTES#The term "autonomous vehicle" is also often used in a colloquial form and is even less well defined. The term is particularly problematic because the word "autonomous" has been used for a long time in the robotics and artificial intelligence research communities to signify systems that have the ability and authority to make decisions independently and self-sufficiently. Due to its imprecise and overly broad meaning, use of the term "autonomous vehicle" is discouraged.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: #NOTES#This term can, and when possible should be, refined by identifying the level of automation. For example, the terms "level 5 ADS-equipped vehicle" and "level 5 automated vehicle" should be interpreted as "ADS-equipped vehicle where the ADS is a level 5 ADS."

properties.documentation: <driving automation> vehicle designed to be operated by a person during part or all of every trip.

driving automation system that provides either sustained lateral or sustained longitudinal vehicle motion control within a specific operational design domain with the expectation that a conventional driver completes the dynamic driving task

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Other driving automation levels include "level 2 driving automation", "level 3 ADS", "level 4 ADS", and "level 5 ADS".

properties.documentation: hardware and software system that is able to perform part or all of the DDT on a sustained basis

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: #NOTES#In contrast to this generic term for any level 1-5 system, the specific term for a level 3-5 system is "Automated Driving System (ADS)." Given the similarity between the generic term, "driving automation system," and the level 3-5-specific term, "Automated Driving System," the latter term is intentionally capitalized when spelled out and reduced to its acronym, "ADS", as much as possible, while "driving automation system" should not be.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Driving automation levels include "level 1 driving automation", "level 2 driving automation", "level 3 ADS", "level 4 ADS", and "level 5 ADS".

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Driving automation levels are defined in ISO/SAE 22736, which is also known as SAE J3026.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: A driving automation system includes any system capable of level 1-5 driving automation.

properties.documentation: <driving automation> ADS-equipped vehicle designed for both driverless operation and operation by a conventional driver for complete trips
all real-time operational and tactical functions required to operate a vehicle in on-road traffic

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: #NOTES#The DDT includes lateral vehicle motion control, longitudinal vehicle motion control, monitoring the driving environment, object and event response execution, manoeuvre planning, and enhancing conspicuousness.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The DDT excludes strategic functions such as trip scheduling and selection of destinations and waypoints.

properties.documentation: <driving automation> response by an ADS to achieve a minimal risk condition upon exit from the defined operational design domain or in response to a system failure
<DDT> person who is able to operate the vehicle if the ADS issues a request to intervene or if s/he otherwise identifies a condition that requires intervention to perform the DDT
ADS designed with the expectation that the fallback-ready user is available to intervene

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Other driving automation levels include "level 1 driving automation", "level 2 driving automation", "level 4 ADS", and "level 5 ADS".

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Level 3 ADSs are typically restricted to operating within a specific ODD.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The user might need to intervene due to an ADS-issued request, a DDT performance-relevant system failure, or other reasons.

properties.documentation: ADS that is capable of operating within a specific ODD and providing its own fallback, without any expectation that a human driver will respond to a request to intervene

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Other driving automation levels include "level 1 driving automation", "level 2 driving automation", "level 3 ADS", and "level 5 ADS".

properties.documentation: ADS that is capable of unconditional (i.e., not ODD-specific) operation and providing its own fallback, without any expectation that a human driver will respond to a request to intervene

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Other driving automation levels include "level 1 driving automation", "level 2 driving automation", "level 3 ADS", and "level 4 ADS".

properties.documentation: set of operating conditions under which a given driving automation system or feature thereof is specifically designed to function

tag.name: Vocab::example
tag.value: ADS-dedicated vehicle designed to operate only within a geographically-defined area, and only during daylight at speeds not to exceed 25 mph.

tag.name: Vocab::example
tag.value: ADS feature designed to operate a vehicle only on fully access-controlled freeways in low-speed traffic, under fair weather conditions and optimal road maintenance conditions (e.g., good lane markings and not under construction).#NOTES#An ADS-dedicated commercial truck is designed to pick up parts from a geofenced sea port and deliver them via a specific route to a distribution center located 30 miles away. The vehicles ODD is limited to day- time operation within the specified sea port and the specific roads that constitute the prescribed route between the sea port and the distribution center.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The conditions might include environmental, geographical, time-of-day, and/or other restrictions.

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The conditions might require the presence or absence of certain traffic or roadway characteristics.

properties.documentation: driving automation system that provides sustained lateral and longitudinal vehicle motion control within a specific operational design domain with the expectation that a conventional driver completes the object and event detection and response

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: Other driving automation levels include "level 1 driving automation", "level 3 ADS", "level 4 ADS", and "level 5 ADS".

properties.documentation: <driving automation> malfunction in a vehicle system that prevents the driving automation system from reliably performing its responsibilities on a sustained basis

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The malfunction may be internal to the driving automation system or part of another vehicle system.

properties.documentation: <ITS> characteristic of a material entity that is or was equipped with communications equipment that is sufficiently physically disconnected such that the vehicle is no longer able to send data to or receive data from connected entities

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: The vehicle on-board equipment might still be present in the vehicle and might even be partially connected, but not in any operational sense.

properties.documentation: <ITS> characteristic of an material entity that is currently unable to send data to or receive data from connected entities
<ITS> characteristic of an material entity that is equipped with communications equipment that is not active or is otherwise unable to send data to or receive data from connected entities
<ITS> characteristic of an material entity that is not and has never been equipped with communications equipment for sending data to or receiving data from connected entities

properties.documentation: vehicle meeting the legal requirements to operate within the driving space of a road

tag.name: Vocab::note
tag.value: #NOTES#While the road network is designed based on certain vehicle characteristics, a "road vehicle" is any vehicle that is allowed to use the road. For example, while roads are designed for vehicles between 2 and 2.5 metres in width, most jurisdictions allow narrower vehicles (e.g., motorcycles) to use the road and may allow wider vehicles (e.g., wide loads) to use the road within certain constraints.
